review_blob:
On tap at pub. I love beets. This was so good. Red brew with a pink head. Bright as hell. Hoppy and beat nose. Subtle beet-earthy flavor with a wine like quality and cereal notes throughout. Balanced well and easily smashed. 

My only question... can I substitute for Jamba Juice?

Can poured into shaker. Copper colored and bright. Lasting sticky white head. Super pine grapefruit nose. One of the most well balanced IPAs I have ever had. Hints of caramel/toffee back and forth with grapefruit. Finish was my favorite. Huge fan of dry hopped brews. This was clearly heavily dry hopped. Little to no grassy notes on the nose. pleasant and lasting resinous after bite. Dangerous IPA as it was easily quaffable. I would compare this to a dry hopped Dales Pale Ale.

Taster GABF 2013. Great aroma. Pours black with thing tan head. Perfectly carbonated. Huge chocolate coffee aroma... like chocolate covered espresso beans. Creamy mouth feel. Sweet roasty and chocolate coffee flavor. Almost no astringency. Great beer.
Bottle at Old Cs. Copper with lasting white head. Sticky lacing. Strong herbal, spicy notes with a hint of citrus. Caramel, quite warming with a great resinous follow through.
Bomber. Dark Amber with off white head. Heavy whiskey and oak notes with toffee aromas. Super chewy and rich. Residual sweetness with a wood hint. Bright, clean and well balanced. Great barley wine.
beer_name: Dry Dock Signature Series Blighs Barleywine Ale

review_blob: Bomber from friends cellar. Dark amber and hazy with a small lasting head. Looks great. Musty sweet and sour with mango aroma. Puckering bretty mouthfeel with medium acidity. Meh. Ill stick to suerette.

Pint on tap poured in a snifter. Beer had a pretty straw-golden color with a white head that dissipated QUICKLY. First sniffs were deceiving as the Belgian yeast dominated the problems. Then, sour milk. Sip. Belgian yeast. Low spiciness... sip... sour milk. really unpleasant.

On tap at brewpub. Bright and light brown, almost dark red, with small lingering head. Aroma of boozy oak, prunes, dark roast coffee and dark chocolate. Medium body with chocolate, coffee, vanilla and subtle roastiness and more chocolate with booze. Quite a boozy beer. Id like to cellar this and let it mellow out a bit.

On tap at brewery. Fun session ale. However, I wouldnt hit it twice. Grainy and malty fresh cut grass citrus nose. Light color and crazy head retention. Slightly grainy flavor blended with a bunch of melon graprefruit. Finishes fairly dry.
Bomber. Motor oil black. Tan head. Malty, roasty coffee molasses, chocolate and more coffee notes. Amazing sweet and roasty flavor with medium warmth. Bottle was one year old. Perfect cellar bottle.

12 OZ can at Fire on the Mountain. Beauty. Soft brown color. Great lasting head. Nose of nutty chocolate and a hint of honey. Well carbonated with a good chewy mouth feel. Chocolate, molasses and honey bunches of oats. Finished clean and dry with low residual sweetness. Could pass the three beer test.
